## 1. One-Line Summary

- The Hook — Yasaka Rakza X features an exceptionally grippy NSS (New Surface System) topsheet that bites the plastic ball fiercely, eliminating slippage and providing supreme confidence in power loops.
- Archetype — Aggressive Looper / Power Spin Attacker.

## 2. Performance Analysis

- Speed & Gears
    - Passive Block Speed: Moderate. The medium-hard sponge absorbs pace well, but the highly grippy topsheet requires slightly active angle adjustment so the ball doesn't pop up.
    - Active Loop Speed: High. When you engage the sponge with proper technique, the power output is robust and penetrating.
    - Linearity vs. Trampoline: Very linear. Unlike older generation ESN rubbers, Rakza X does not have an aggressive, unpredictable trampoline effect. You get exactly what you put into the stroke.
    - Mid-Distance Carry: Excellent. The rubber holds enough energy to maintain a deep, heavy trajectory even when counter-looping from two or three steps back.

- Spin Generation
    - Top-End Spin: Massive. This is the hallmark of Rakza X. The anti-slip topsheet grabs the poly ball exceptionally well, creating heavy, diving topspin.
    - Opening Loop: Highly reliable. Lifting heavy backspin is remarkably easy because the topsheet catches the ball securely, allowing for high-arc, slow-spin openers.
    - Serve Quality: Fantastic. The firm, grippy surface allows for thin brushing, generating massive backspin and sidespin on short serves without the ball bouncing off too early.

- Control & Short Game
    - Touch Play: Good, due to the linear nature of the sponge. Pushes can be kept very low and short if you control the incoming spin.
    - Spin Sensitivity: High. Because the topsheet grips the ball so well, it also reads the opponent's spin heavily. Lazy blocks will fly off the table.
    - Flick Window: Generous for the banana flick (Chiquita) due to the grip, but requires a decisive stroke to overpower incoming spin on straight flicks.

- Throw Angle (Arc)
    - Trajectory: Medium-high to High.
    - Arc Behavior: The ball leaves the racket with a pronounced safety arc, dipping violently at the end of its flight path due to the heavy spin.

- Spin-Interaction Behavior
    - Against Heavy Topspin: Performs brilliantly in counter-topspin rallies, provided you actively brush the ball. Passive blocking against heavy topspin requires closing the racket angle carefully.
    - Against Heavy Backspin: One of the best ESN rubbers for this. The NSS topsheet bites into the backspin and reverses it effortlessly with a strong upward stroke.
    - Error Pattern: Missing long. If a player relies on sponge bounce rather than brushing, the high throw angle combined with incoming spin can cause the ball to sail past the baseline.

## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve
    - Incredible grip allows for heavy spin variation. You can really feel the ball biting into the topsheet on ghost serves and heavy underspin.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Requires soft hands. The linear sponge helps, but the topsheet will react to the opponent's spin if you aren't actively guiding the touch.
    - Flick: Forehand flicks require a good snap of the wrist to overcome the rubber's spin sensitivity.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Phenomenal. The topsheet grabs the ball easily over the table, allowing you to lift and curve the ball with heavy top-sidespin.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Unmatched safety. You can confidently attack heavy pushes without fear of the ball slipping off the rubber.
    - Continuous Looping: Rewards good footwork and full strokes. The linear catapult means you won't get exhausted, but you do need to supply the power.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Devastating. When hitting through the sponge, the ball carries tremendous speed and rotational weight.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: Excellent grip allows you to loop over the opponent's loop easily, dictating the rally.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Good, but requires a firm wrist. A pure flat punch is less effective than a slightly topspun active block.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Manageable, but not its strong suit. The grippy topsheet catches incoming spin, meaning you must constantly adjust your bat angle.
    - Active Block: Highly effective. Adding a slight forward pressing motion engages the sponge and nullifies the incoming spin.

- Smash & Flat Hit
    - Average. The medium-hard sponge supports hitting, but the high throw angle and spin-oriented topsheet make flat hitting less intuitive than with softer, flatter-throwing rubbers.

- Defense
    - Chop: Surprisingly viable for occasional fishing or emergency chopping due to the linear sponge, though it is quite fast.
    - Lob: Excellent. The high arc and strong spin generation allow for deep, kicking lobs that are difficult to smash.

