## 6. Pros & Cons

- Pros
    - Absolutely no slippage on the plastic ball; incredible grip.
    - Highly linear power output, meaning excellent predictability in rallies.
    - Exceptional safety and high arc when lifting heavy backspin.
- Cons
    - Spin sensitivity makes passive blocking difficult against heavy topspin.
    - Heavier than average, which can make the overall paddle weight cumbersome.
    - Requires active stroke mechanics; it will not play the shot for you.

---

## 7. Recommended Users & Pairings

- Who Should Buy This: Aggressive topspin players who prioritize grip, spin, and linear power over bouncy trampoline effects. Players who struggle with the ball slipping on their opening loops.
- Who Should Avoid This: Flat hitters, passive blockers, and beginners who lack the fundamental stroke mechanics to engage a medium-hard sponge.
- Complementary Rubber Pairings (Opposite Side): Yasaka Rakza 7 (for a slightly softer, more controlled backhand), or a softer ESN rubber like Tibhar Evolution FX-P or Fastarc C-1 to balance the weight.

---

## 8. Value & Alternatives

- Value Verdict: Excellent. Rakza X is highly durable. The topsheet maintains its grip significantly longer than many standard ESN rubbers, making it a great long-term investment.
- Similar Alternatives
    - Same Brand: Yasaka Rakza 7 (Softer, slightly more bouncy, slightly less absolute top-end spin), Yasaka Rakza Z (Tacky version, even more grip but slower).
    - Rival Brand: Nittaku Fastarc G-1 (Very similar high grip and linear feel, G-1 has a slightly harder feel), Tibhar Evolution MX-P (MX-P is faster and has more trampoline effect).
- Closest Feel Match Summary: Plays most similarly to Nittaku Fastarc G-1, acting as a highly reliable, heavy-duty spin machine that demands proper technique but rewards it with massive rotation and stable arcs.

